threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

attributes.magic: ELF 32-bit MSB executable, Motorola m68k, 68020, version 1 (SYSV), statically linked, not stripped

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: The sample is a DDoS botnet agent, likely belonging to the Mirai or Gafgyt/Bashlite families, targeting Linux-based IoT architectures (AArch64). It features a wide array of specialized flooding functions including SendUDP, SendTCP, SendHTTP, SendSNMP, and SendVSE. The binary contains numerous hardcoded browser User-Agent strings and HTTP templates used for masquerading malicious traffic. Concrete malicious behaviors include persistence via watchdog manipulation (/dev/watchdog), remote command processing (processCmd), and the ability to execute shell commands via /bin/sh. Relevant IOCs include the specific flood function names and the presence of various device-specific watchdog paths.
